@page "/Prepare"
@{
    Layout = "_Layout";
    ViewData["Title"] = "Prepare for Your Design Conversation";
} 

<!-- Hero -->
<section class="py-24 bg-surface-container-low border-b border-outline-variant/20">
  <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto px-8">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <span class="font-label text-secondary tracking-widest text-xs font-bold uppercase block mb-4">Discovery Preparation</span>
      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-headline leading-tight mb-6">Before we talk about your house, think about your life.</h1>
      <p class="text-base md:text-xl text-on-surface-variant font-body font-light leading-relaxed mb-8">
        The home we design together may be the last one you ever build. It needs to support your family through stages of life you can see clearly, stages you can almost see, and stages you can barely imagine. The more clearly you've thought about all of them before our first deep conversation, the better the result will be.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg text-on-surface-variant font-body font-light leading-relaxed">
        This page will walk you through the thinking I'd like you to do before we sit down together. You don't need all the answers — you need to have sat with the questions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Sticky section nav -->
<div class="sticky top-[73px] z-40 bg-surface border-b border-outline-variant/20 py-4">
  <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto px-8">
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 items-center">
      <span class="font-label text-[10px] tracking-widest uppercase text-on-surface-variant hidden md:block mr-2">Jump to:</span>
      <a href="#homes-past" class="font-label text-xs tracking-wide text-on-surface-variant border border-outline-variant/40 rounded-full px-4 py-2 hover:border-secondary hover:text-secondary transition-all">Your Past Homes</a>
      <a href="#looking-forward" class="font-label text-xs tracking-wide text-on-surface-variant border border-outline-variant/40 rounded-full px-4 py-2 hover:border-secondary hover:text-secondary transition-all">Looking Forward</a>
      <a href="#occupancy" class="font-label text-xs tracking-wide text-on-surface-variant border border-outline-variant/40 rounded-full px-4 py-2 hover:border-secondary hover:text-secondary transition-all">Who Lives Here</a>
      <a href="#rooms" class="font-label text-xs tracking-wide text-on-surface-variant border border-outline-variant/40 rounded-full px-4 py-2 hover:border-secondary hover:text-secondary transition-all">Your Rooms</a>
      <a href="#room-lists" class="font-label text-xs tracking-wide text-on-surface-variant border border-outline-variant/40 rounded-full px-4 py-2 hover:border-secondary hover:text-secondary transition-all">Room Reference</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ─── SECTION 1: Past Homes ─── -->
<section class="py-24 bg-surface" id="homes-past">
  <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto px-8">
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-12 gap-8 lg:gap-16 items-start">
      <div class="lg:col-span-7 space-y-8">
        <div>
          <span class="font-label text-secondary tracking-widest text-xs font-bold uppercase block mb-3">Step One</span>
          <h2 class="text-4xl font-headline leading-snug mb-6">Start with the homes you've already lived in.</h2>
          <div class="space-y-5 text-on-surface-variant text-lg font-body leading-relaxed font-light">
            <p>Every home you've occupied has taught you something — most of it through friction. The awkward kitchen that made cooking feel like a battle. The bedroom that was always too cold. The living room that somehow never felt right no matter how you arranged it. The front door that everyone ignored in favor of the back. These aren't trivial inconveniences. They are design failures, and they are data.</p>
            <p>The homes that worked well have taught you something too — even if it's harder to articulate. The morning light in a particular room. The way the kitchen opened to the backyard. The hallway wide enough for two people to pass without apologizing. Pay attention to those memories as well.</p>
            <p>Before our conversation, I'd like you to mentally walk through every home you've lived in as an adult and ask yourself honestly: what worked, what didn't, and why. The goal isn't to catalogue complaints — it's to build a clear picture of what your life actually needs from a house, as opposed to what looks good when you're browsing floor plans online.</p>
            <p>My wife and I scrapped our initial plans after this exercise and built a house that fits like a glove.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-secondary pl-6 my-2">
          <p class="font-serif italic text-2xl text-primary leading-relaxed">My favorite client insight was: 'My kitchen garbage can has been in the way for 50 years.' Her kitchen garbage now has a home and she tells me about it every time I see her. Little things matter.</p>
        </blockquote>

        <div class="space-y-5 text-on-surface-variant text-lg font-body leading-relaxed font-light">
          <p>Think about your <strong class="text-on-surface font-semibold">current home</strong> especially carefully. You've adapted to it so thoroughly that you may not notice its failures anymore. Walk through it with fresh eyes and try to notice the workarounds you've built into your daily routine — the counter junk piles up on because there's no good place for it, the path you take around the furniture, the room you almost never use.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Prompt cards -->
      <div class="lg:col-span-5 space-y-4 lg:pt-10">
        <p class="font-label text-[10px] tracking-widest uppercase text-on-surface-variant mb-4">Questions to sit with</p>

        <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 border border-outline-variant/20 space-y-2">
          <p class="font-headline text-base text-primary">What has frustrated you most?</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed">In each home, what did you work around, complain about, or wish daily was different? Consider rooms, flow, storage, light, noise, and temperature.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 border border-outline-variant/20 space-y-2">
          <p class="font-headline text-base text-primary">What room did everyone actually use?</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed">And what room sat empty? Why did one space draw people in while another was avoided? What made the difference?</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 border border-outline-variant/20 space-y-2">
          <p class="font-headline text-base text-primary">What have you never had enough of?</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed">Storage. Counter space. Natural light. Quiet. Privacy. A place to put things down when you walk in the door. Identify your chronic shortages.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 border border-outline-variant/20 space-y-2">
          <p class="font-headline text-base text-primary">What do you never want to repeat?</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed">If there is one thing — one room, one layout decision, one feature — that you would eliminate from every future home, what is it?</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 border border-outline-variant/20 space-y-2">
          <p class="font-headline text-base text-primary">What was great?</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed">If you've lived in a home — or visited one — where something felt exactly correct, try to identify what it was. The proportions of a room, a view, a flow, a quality of light. These should be in your next home.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto px-8"><div class="border-t border-outline-variant/20"></div></div>

<!-- ─── SECTION 2: Looking Forward ─── -->
<section class="py-24 bg-surface-container-low" id="looking-forward">
  <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto px-8">

    <div class="max-w-3xl mb-16">
      <span class="font-label text-secondary tracking-widest text-xs font-bold uppercase block mb-3">Step Two</span>
      <h2 class="text-4xl font-headline leading-snug mb-6">Now look forward. As far as you can.</h2>
      <div class="space-y-5 text-on-surface-variant text-lg font-body leading-relaxed font-light">
        <p>Unlike software, where you can release a new version, you can't release a new version of a house. This may be the last one you ever build — and it will hopefully be the one you live in longest. That means the decisions you make in the design phase will shape your daily life not just for a decade, but potentially for three or four of them.</p>
        <p>Most people design for their life as it is right now, or perhaps as it will be in two or three years. That's understandable — the near future seems clear but the more distant future is not. A well-designed home should serve you through the full arc of life you'll live in it. The goal of this exercise is to stretch your thinking forward and give the design a longer time horizon to work with.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Timeline -->
    <div class="space-y-8 max-w-4xl">

      <!-- 10 years -->
      <div class="timeline-item flex gap-8 items-start">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-14 h-14 rounded-full bg-secondary text-white flex items-center justify-center shadow-md">
          <span class="font-headline text-sm font-bold">10</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex-1 pb-10">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-headline text-primary mb-2">Ten years from now</h3>
          <p class="text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed mb-5">This should be relatively clear. Children will be older — perhaps in school, perhaps starting to leave, or maybe more of them. Careers may shift. If you're working from home now, will you still be? If you're raising young children, what happens when they become teenagers? Think concretely about this version of your household.</p>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
            <div class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 border border-outline-variant/20">
              <p class="text-sm font-body text-on-surface-variant leading-relaxed">How many people will be living here? What are their ages?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 border border-outline-variant/20">
              <p class="text-sm font-body text-on-surface-variant leading-relaxed">Will children still be at home — or will some rooms become available for new purposes?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 border border-outline-variant/20">
              <p class="text-sm font-body text-on-surface-variant leading-relaxed">Will your work situation look the same? Do you need a home office, or might you need two?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 border border-outline-variant/20">
              <p class="text-sm font-body text-on-surface-variant leading-relaxed">Are there hobbies or activities you expect to take on more seriously as you have more time?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 20 years -->
      <div class="timeline-item flex gap-8 items-start">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-14 h-14 rounded-full bg-primary text-white flex items-center justify-center shadow-md">
          <span class="font-headline text-sm font-bold">20</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex-1 pb-10">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-headline text-primary mb-2">Twenty years from now</h3>
          <p class="text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed mb-5">This horizon gets harder — and more important. Some children will be fully grown and gone. You and your spouse may be looking at an empty nest for the first time. Aging parents might enter the picture. Retirement may be approaching or underway. Your physical needs and limitations may be different. Design decisions made now — step-free thresholds, wider hallways, ground-floor bedroom access, a guest suite that could become an in-law suite — will feel either prescient or painful from this vantage point.</p>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
            <div class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 border border-outline-variant/20">
              <p class="text-sm font-body text-on-surface-variant leading-relaxed">Will adult children and grandchildren visit frequently? Do they need dedicated guest space?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 border border-outline-variant/20">
              <p class="text-sm font-body text-on-surface-variant leading-relaxed">Might aging parents need to live with you, or nearby? What would that require?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 border border-outline-variant/20">
              <p class="text-sm font-body text-on-surface-variant leading-relaxed">Could this be your retirement home? What does that version of daily life look like?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 border border-outline-variant/20">
              <p class="text-sm font-body text-on-surface-variant leading-relaxed">Are stairs a potential problem for you or your spouse at this age?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 30 years -->
      <div class="flex gap-8 items-start">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-14 h-14 rounded-full bg-surface border-2 border-outline-variant text-on-surface-variant flex items-center justify-center">
          <span class="font-headline text-sm font-bold">30</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex-1">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-headline text-primary mb-2">Thirty years from now</h3>
          <p class="text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed mb-5">This is the hardest horizon to think about clearly — and for that reason it is worth attempting even if you can't see it fully. Many families have stayed in a custom home for three and four decades. At thirty years out, you may be in your sixties, seventies, or eighties. The question is not whether you can imagine that version of yourself in detail, but whether the house you're designing today would still be serving you well — or whether it would have become a burden. If you know the house has an expiration date for you I can make sure it works for your timeline.</p>
          <div class="bg-surface rounded-xl p-6 border border-outline-variant/30">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-secondary text-2xl mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0">lightbulb</span>
              <p class="text-on-surface-variant text-sm font-body leading-relaxed">The most common regret in this conversation is the staircase. A home designed around two stories is efficient today and potentially inaccessible in thirty years. This doesn't mean your home has to be a single-story — but it means the decision needs to be well thought out.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto px-8"><div class="border-t border-outline-variant/20"></div></div>

<!-- ─── SECTION 3: Occupancy ─── -->
<section class="py-24 bg-surface" id="occupancy">
  <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto px-8">
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-12 gap-8 lg:gap-16 items-start">
      <div class="lg:col-span-7 space-y-6">
        <div>
          <span class="font-label text-secondary tracking-widest text-xs font-bold uppercase block mb-3">Step Three</span>
          <h2 class="text-4xl font-headline leading-snug mb-6">Think carefully about who will be in this home — and when.</h2>
          <div class="space-y-5 text-on-surface-variant text-lg font-body leading-relaxed font-light">
            <p>A home that works beautifully for four people can feel wrong for two, and vice versa. Occupancy is not just about bedroom count — it's about how many people are moving through the kitchen at once, how many people need quiet at the same time, how shared or private the daily rhythms of your household are.</p>
            <p>Consider both the people who will <strong class="text-on-surface font-semibold">live here full time</strong> and those who will <strong class="text-on-surface font-semibold">visit regularly</strong>. Extended family, adult children returning for summers or holidays, long-term guests, parents who stay for weeks at a time — these visitors have real space requirements, and a home that doesn't account for them forces awkward compromises every time they arrive.</p>
            <p>Map this out across all three time horizons, and map it honestly. The goal is not to build a hotel. It's to build a home that doesn't put your family in an impossible situation when life changes.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="lg:col-span-5 space-y-4 lg:pt-10">
        <p class="font-label text-[10px] tracking-widest uppercase text-on-surface-variant mb-2">For each time horizon, consider:</p>

        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-4 p-5 bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl border border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-secondary text-xl mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0">person</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-headline text-sm text-primary mb-1">Full-time residents</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed">How many people live here every day? What are their ages, schedules, and daily rhythms? Do they need privacy from each other, or is shared space the norm?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-4 p-5 bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl border border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-secondary text-xl mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0">group</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-headline text-sm text-primary mb-1">Regular visitors</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed">Who visits most often, and for how long? Overnight guests, extended family, adult children home from school, grandchildren? How many beds does this require?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-4 p-5 bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl border border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-secondary text-xl mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0">family_restroom</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-headline text-sm text-primary mb-1">Life stage transitions</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed">Children leaving home, parents moving in, grandchildren visiting for weeks at a time. Which transitions do you anticipate, and what space do they require when they happen?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-4 p-5 bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl border border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-secondary text-xl mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0">meeting_room</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-headline text-sm text-primary mb-1">Gatherings and events</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed">Do you host holidays, family reunions, or large dinners? How many people need to sit at a table, gather in a living space, or find a place to sleep?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto px-8"><div class="border-t border-outline-variant/20"></div></div>

<!-- ─── SECTION 4: Rooms ─── -->
<section class="py-24 bg-surface-container-low" id="rooms">
  <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto px-8">

    <div class="max-w-3xl mb-16">
      <span class="font-label text-secondary tracking-widest text-xs font-bold uppercase block mb-3">Step Four</span>
      <h2 class="text-4xl font-headline leading-snug mb-6">Think room by room — but think deeper than a list.</h2>
      <div class="space-y-5 text-on-surface-variant text-lg font-body leading-relaxed font-light">
        <p>Most people approach a room list as a count of bedrooms and bathrooms. I want to understand not just what rooms your home should have, but what life happens inside each one.</p>
        <p>For every room on your list, I'd like you to think through three things before our conversation. The better you can answer these, the better the room will be designed around your actual life rather than a generic version of it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Three-column framework -->
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-8 mb-20">
      <div class="bg-surface rounded-xl p-8 border border-outline-variant/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-secondary/10 flex items-center justify-center mb-5">
          <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-secondary text-2xl">directions_run</span>
        </div>
        <h3 class="text-xl font-headline text-primary mb-3">Activities</h3>
        <p class="text-on-surface-variant text-sm font-body leading-relaxed mb-4">What actually happens in this room? Be specific and honest — not what you aspire to do there, but what you will actually do. List every activity, including the mundane ones.</p>
        <div class="space-y-2">
          <p class="text-xs text-on-surface-variant font-body italic">Examples for a kitchen: cooking dinner, morning coffee routine, kids doing homework at the island, video calls at the counter, meal prep for the week, informal family meals, guest gathering while cooking…</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-surface rounded-xl p-8 border border-outline-variant/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-secondary/10 flex items-center justify-center mb-5">
          <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-secondary text-2xl">chair</span>
        </div>
        <h3 class="text-xl font-headline text-primary mb-3">Furniture</h3>
        <p class="text-on-surface-variant text-sm font-body leading-relaxed mb-4">List every piece of furniture the room needs to contain. Include sizes if you know them, and note any pieces you already own that must fit. A room can't be the right size if we don't know what has to live in it.</p>
        <div class="space-y-2">
          <p class="text-xs text-on-surface-variant font-body italic">Examples for a master bedroom: king bed with nightstands, upholstered chair and floor lamp, TV console, bench at foot of bed, exercise bike in corner…</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-surface rounded-xl p-8 border border-outline-variant/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-secondary/10 flex items-center justify-center mb-5">
          <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-secondary text-2xl">inventory_2</span>
        </div>
        <h3 class="text-xl font-headline text-primary mb-3">Storage</h3>
        <p class="text-on-surface-variant text-sm font-body leading-relaxed mb-4">What does this room need to store — and how much of it? Dedicated storage is one of the most under-designed elements in residential homes. Think about what belongs in this room versus what ends up there because it has no better home.</p>
        <div class="space-y-2">
          <p class="text-xs text-on-surface-variant font-body italic">Examples for a mudroom: shoes for 7 people, backpacks, coats, outdoor gear, dog leashes, sports equipment, seasonal items, cleaning supplies…</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ─── SECTION 5: Room Reference Lists ─── -->
<section class="py-24 bg-surface" id="room-lists">
  <div class="max-w-screen-2xl mx-auto px-8">

    <div class="max-w-3xl mb-14">
      <span class="font-label text-secondary tracking-widest text-xs font-bold uppercase block mb-3">Room Reference</span>
      <h2 class="text-4xl font-headline leading-snug mb-6">A reference list to think from.</h2>
      <p class="text-on-surface-variant text-lg font-body leading-relaxed font-light">
        Use these lists as a prompt, not a checklist. Your home probably won't contain all of these rooms, and you might want rooms that aren't listed. The goal is to make sure you've considered possibilities you might not have thought of on your own — and made a conscious decision about each one rather than accepting defaults.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 lg:gap-16">

      <!-- Common rooms -->
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
          <div class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-secondary flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
            <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-white text-base">home</span>
          </div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-headline text-primary">Commonly included rooms</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-on-surface-variant font-body leading-relaxed mb-6">These are the rooms that appear in most residential designs. Treat each as a decision, not an assumption — even the obvious ones benefit from deliberate thought.</p>

        <div class="space-y-2">
          <!-- Common room groups -->
          <div class="mb-5">
            <p class="font-label text-[10px] tracking-widest uppercase text-on-surface-variant mb-3">Living & Gathering</p>
            <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
              <span class="room-tag"><span class="material-symbols-outlined text-sm">living</span>Living Room / Great Room</span>
              <span class="room-tag"><span class="material-symbols-outlined text-sm">dining</span>Dining Room</span>
              <span class="room-tag"><span class="material-symbols-outlined text-sm">countertops</span>Kitchen</span>
              <span class="room-tag"><span class="material-symbols-outlined text-sm">shelves</span>Pantry</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="mb-5">
            <p class="font-label text-[10px] tracking-widest uppercase text-on-surface-variant mb-3">Sleeping & Bathing</p>
            <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
              <span class="room-tag"><span class="material-symbols-outlined text-sm">bed</span>Master Bedroom</span>
              <span class="room-tag"><span class="material-symbols-outlined text-sm">bathtub</span>Master Bathroom</span>
              <span class="room-tag"><span class="material-symbols-outlined text-sm">bedroom_child</span>Children's Bedrooms</span>
              <span class="room-tag"><span class="material-symbols-outlined text-sm">bedroom_child</span>Guest Bedroom</span>
              <span class="room-tag"><span class="material-symbols-outlined text-sm">shower</span>Bathrooms</span>
              <span class="room-tag"><span class="material-symbols-outlined text-sm">checkroom</span>Walk-in Closet(s)</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="mb-5">
            <p class="font-label text-[10px] tracking-widest uppercase text-on-surface-variant mb-3">Utility & Transition</p>
